String is immutable because its class is final, its internal state is private and final, there are no setters, and any modification creates a new object. Immutability provides security, thread safety, caching in String Pool, and hashcode stability.



Exactly, you caught the hidden problem. This is one of the most important points in immutability.

final does not make the object immutable. It only makes the reference fixed.

Example:

class Address {
    String city;

    Address(String city) {
        this.city = city;
    }

    void setCity(String city) {
        this.city = city;
    }
}


final class Student {

    private final Address address;

    Student(Address address) {
        this.address = address;
    }

    public Address getAddress() {
        return address;
    }
}

Now:

Address a = new Address("Jaipur");

Student s = new Student(a);

s.getAddress().setCity("Delhi");

System.out.println(s.getAddress().city);

Output:

Delhi

But we said Student is immutable? 😅
Actually it is not truly immutable.

Why?

Because:

private final Address address;

means:

Student
  |
  v
Address object

The arrow cannot move.

This is not allowed:

address = new Address("Mumbai"); // ❌

But the object that arrow points to can still change:

Before:

Student
   |
   v
Address("Jaipur")


After:

Student
   |
   v
Address("Delhi")
Solution: Defensive Copying

Immutable class should not give the original mutable object.

final class Student {

    private final Address address;

    Student(Address address) {
        this.address = new Address(address.city);
    }


    public Address getAddress() {
        return new Address(address.city);
    }
}

Now:

Address a = new Address("Jaipur");

Student s = new Student(a);

a.setCity("Delhi");

System.out.println(s.getAddress().city);

Output:

Jaipur

Because Student has its own copy.